Patient is 52 y/o male with coronary artery disease s/p MI and CABG, peripheral vascular disease, hepatitis C referred to clinic due to thrombocytopenia. Decreased platelets present since at least 6/2021 and there are in range 37,000-61,0000/ul. Patient denies bleeding, night sweats, fevers, weight loss. He noted easy bruising.
For 20 years he reports drinking weekly 12 beers and 4 shots of liquor.
Abdomen US 2022-09-03 -coarsened liver echotexture with increased liver echogenicity consistent with
underlying hepatocellular disease, spleen 11 cm, cholelithiasis without evidence of cholecystitis.
Previous tests:
2022-04-14 WBC 6.8, Hb 13.4, plt 40
2022-08-31 WBC 6.4, Hb 9.7, plt 39, CMP abnormal for sodium 129, glucose 273, creat 1.76, PT 13.3
2022-09-02 WBC 5.5, Hb 10.4, plt 53, ferritin 146, trans sat 19, folate 22, vit B12 197
During initial visit in clinic on 2022-09-23 WBC 6.7, Hb 12.6, platelets 50
Peripheral blood smear showed few dysplastic lymphocytes and increased teardrop cells
LDH and haptoglobin normal
Reticulocytes 2.6
SPEP, IFE no monoclonal protein
HCV , HIV nonreactive
Patient started taking vitamin B12 pills
Interval History
Patient returned to clinic for interval evaluation. He had once nosebleeds few days ago, no other bleeding issues. He continues drinking alcohol but cut down to weekly, no withdrawal symptoms. No night sweats, fevers, weight loss, recurrent infections. He reports compliance with vitamin B12 pills.

Patient is 52 y/o male with coronary artery disease s/p MI and CABG, peripheral vascular disease, hepatitis C, alcohol use referred to clinic due to thrombocytopenia.
#1 Thrombocytopenia
Laboratory tests today showed WBC 4.4, Hb 12.4, platelets 33
Peripheral blood smear showed few dysplastic lymphocytes and increased teardrop cells
Platelets worsening despite improvement in vit B12
Recommended alcohol cessation, patient refused help of our social worker
Patient will be scheduled for bone marrow biopsy
Repeat CBC in 2 weeks
#2 Vitamin B12 deficiency
Vitamin B12
Continue vitamin B12 pills
Follow up in 6 weeks
